arch:property.oc:show_val: We have recorded the multiple scapulae (four cattle, one red deer) from this unit, along with a few miscellaneous bones that came with them, and the rest of the bone from the unit. X1 is younger and smaller than X2. X5 seems to be older/bigger than X1, although it is hard to be sure given that it is fragmentary and worked, and the same side as X2 (more its size range). X3 is a red deer. So the four scapulae, while two rights and two lefts, are from four different animals. This recalls the set of four mandibles north of B. 49 (I think; in the 40x40 in 2006), found in pairs but from four animals; and the various paired elements from different animals, often male and female. X15, which came in later, is from a fifth animal, as it is even younger and smaller than X1, although fused (fairly recently). There is also a small hunk of large mammal scapula blade, X2, that probably goes with one of the others but is quite deteriorated. The X-finds are rounded out by X4, a large piece of cattle metatarsal, rather weathered but much less fragmented than usual, and X6, a worn and weathered cattle astragalus that seems to have been used as a knucklebone, and was found right up against the pot. Outside it rather than in it, though, as I understood it. Still, interesting in light of the in situ plaster vessel in the Istanbul area in 2006, which was full of sheep/goat astragali. While this is defined as a cluster, it looks as though the whole leveling deposit was collected under this number, as there is a further collection of bones that do not appear to have anything to do with a special deposit. They are mostly sheep-size with a certain amount of large mammal, moderately fragmented and nearly all with a dark brown patina. Fairly even body part distribution, with no feet below the metapodials. Is this hand-picked, or a genuine pattern? Likewise the lack of digestion (there is some gnawing) may be due to the lack of small pieces; few are less than 3 cm. Diagnostics are mostly sheep/goat, with some pig and cattle. Surface condition variable but mostly somewhat worn. Not much burning, all low temperature. No coherence. Looks like dirty fill. Sample 2 >4 mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded completely. Moderate size sample, similar in character to the non-special deposit material from the unit, except with smaller pieces: highly fragmented, mostly little crumbles. There is some foot material here, although not a lot, and few other diagnostics. Mostly sheep-size with a little large mammal. A few bits of scapula blade may belong to the special deposits. Mostly has the dark patina, with a small amount of low temperature burning, mostly in the tiny bits. A couple of bird specimens and some probable amphibian microfauna. Looks like dirty fill.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
